\begin_layout Chapter
Logic and Mathematical Reasoning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Proposition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A proposition is a declarative sentence that declares a fact.
 It may be true or false in itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Propositional Calculus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This calculus comprises of mathematics using 
\series bold
true
\series default
 and 
\series bold
false 
\series default
statements, or equivalently, 
\series bold
1 
\series default
and 
\series bold
0 
\series default
in binary algebra.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To represent statements in propositional calculus, we use 
\series bold
propositional variables
\series default
.
 Examples are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
P: Joseph is 18 years old.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Q: There are exactly 2 primes between 1 and 4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Logical Connectives or Operators
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are some basic logical connectives that are used everywhere.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Negation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a proposition, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim p$
\end_inset

 is called the negation of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 An example is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $p\equiv$
\end_inset

 I am the president of India.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\sim p\equiv$
\end_inset

 I am 
\series bold
not
\series default
 the president of India.
\end_layout

