\begin_layout Subsection
Conjunction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is some proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is another proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, then the conjunction of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is written as 
\begin_inset Formula $p\wedge q$
\end_inset

.
 In common language, it is called as 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
and
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 or, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
but
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 An example is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $p\equiv$
\end_inset


\series medium
 It is rainy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $q\equiv$
\end_inset

 It is cold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $p\wedge q\equiv$
\end_inset

 It is rainy 
\series bold
and
\series default
 cold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
But
\series default
 is used in the case when the propositions are opposite in happening.
 Like if 
\begin_inset Formula $q\equiv$
\end_inset

It is hot, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\wedge q\equiv$
\end_inset

 It is rainy 
\series bold
but
\series default
 hot.
\end_layout

