\begin_layout Subsection
Disjunction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is some proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is another proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, then the disjunction of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is written as 
\begin_inset Formula $p\vee q$
\end_inset

.
 However, there are two types of disjunction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Inclusive disjunction (OR)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The common symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\vee$
\end_inset

 holds for inclusive disjunction.
 In common language, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\vee q$
\end_inset

 is read as 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
or 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 The final value is true if any of the parent propositions is true.
\end_layout

