\begin_layout Subsection
Conditional
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A conditional of propositions 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is written as 
\begin_inset Formula $p\rightarrow q$
\end_inset

, meaning 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

if 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Here, the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
hypothesis 
\series default
or 
\series bold
premie 
\series default
or
\series bold
 antecedant
\series default
, and the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
conclusion 
\series default
or
\series bold
 consequent
\series default
.
 The idea is: if the first proposition is true, then is the statement saying
 the second proposition is true due to the first, true? An example is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $p\equiv$
\end_inset

 I am teaching you.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $q\equiv$
\end_inset

 Good days will come.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $p\rightarrow q\equiv$
\end_inset

 If I teach you, good days will come.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If I teach you and good days come, then the first proposition resulted into
 second (True).
 If I don't teach you, you'll say I didn't teach you so, it didn't matter
 whether good days came or not (True).
 But if I teach you and good days don't come, you'll feel cheated (False).
 Got the idea?
\end_layout

