\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Truth Table for Converse, Inverse, Contrapositive
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It follows that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
The conditional is logically equivalent to contrapositive, and so is converse
 equivalent to inverse.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Biconditional or Bi-implication or Equivalence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So, a biconditional of propositions 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is written as 
\begin_inset Formula $p\leftrightarrow q$
\end_inset

.
 It means 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Here, the idea is: is 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 true if 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is true? So, if 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is true and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is true, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\leftrightarrow q$
\end_inset

 is true.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is false, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is false, then the conclusion is false but the hypothesis is also false,
 so the answer is true.
 In other cases, it's false.
 Think of biconditional as a conditional in both directions.
 Logically, it is 
\begin_inset Formula $p\leftrightarrow q\equiv(p\rightarrow q)\wedge(q\rightarrow p)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

